For each of the {= evidence_facet =} pediatric-health philanthropy disclosure facets listed below, supply source-backed records for {= pediatric_health_org =}+ canonical public pediatric-health organizations per facet, with {= url =}+ official public URLs for each organization/facet pair.

The task is an evidence audit of public disclosure surfaces, not a funder ranking, outreach list, giving strategy, grant strategy, or legal / medical / financial advice task. Ignore contacts, donation instructions, proposal tactics, and donor-advice language unless the same page also carries one of the public disclosure facts below.

Disclosure facets:
- `giving_vehicle_acceptance`: official evidence that the organization accepts donor-advised fund grants, DAF Direct, donor-advised fund gifts, or a comparable formal donor-directed / named public giving mechanism that is accepted by, routed to, or presented for the submitted organization. Generic profile chrome such as Donate Today, "100% stays local," fundraising-program modules, or "Programs That Support" is not enough by itself.
- `pediatric_priority_statement`: official source wording for pediatric, children's health, maternal-child health, pediatric research, care, grantmaking, program, impact, funding, or strategic priorities that are stated for the submitted organization, project, foundation, center, or named entity-specific profile. Profile wording can count when it is genuinely organization-specific; repeated local-funds / areas-of-greatest-need / treatments / equipment / research / child-life template language does not by itself fill this facet.
- `partnership_or_sponsorship_boundary`: official public evidence about institutional partnership criteria or fiscal-sponsorship boundaries, including providing fiscal sponsorship, requiring a qualified fiscal sponsor, explicitly not providing fiscal sponsorship, being a fiscally sponsored pediatric-health project, or narrow public partnership criteria.

Use the canonical public organization/project identity as `pediatric_health_org`; page type, giving mechanism, DAF or planned-giving label, campaign or event name, report title, fiscal-sponsor relationship, source-profile family, and disclosure-facet labels belong in the evidence context or `answer`, not in that organization name. Distinct legal entities or named pediatric-health projects still count when public sources treat them as separate public identities.

Rows should use official or institutionally controlled sources for the named organization, its affiliated hospital / research institution / foundation, or the named fiscal sponsor or umbrella organization when that page itself identifies the pediatric-health organization and relationship. An umbrella, fiscal-sponsor, affiliated-institution, network, profile, or broad program source can establish identity or relationship, but it supports the facet only when the facet disclosure is genuinely specific to the submitted organization or project and to the submitted facet. A source-family profile page is eligible when its own entity-specific profile text, section, report entry, policy, or program description carries the required disclosure; reusable profile chrome or network-template copy is only background. Generic boilerplate on a multi-organization directory, broad profile network, fundraising program, event campaign, or corporate-partner page is not reusable as facet evidence for every listed member. Official annual reports, strategic plans, impact reports, grantmaking pages, public policy / procedure pages, giving pages, and program pages can count. Third-party charity databases, broad nonprofit profiles, press coverage, search results, donor-advice sites, and generic event pages do not count as the disclosure source.

Requirements:
- The page must communicate that it is an official or institutionally controlled source for the named organization or a directly relevant affiliated institution, foundation, fiscal sponsor, or umbrella organization.
- The page must clearly identify the named organization, project, foundation, center, or a legal / common alias and tie it to pediatric, children's health, maternal-child health, pediatric research, or child/family health work.
- The page must substantively support the disclosure required by `evidence_facet`: an accepted, routed, or entity-presented formal giving vehicle for `giving_vehicle_acceptance`; named-organization-specific pediatric-health priority, strategy, program, care, research, grantmaking, impact, or funding wording for `pediatric_priority_statement`; or concrete institutional partnership / fiscal-sponsorship boundary evidence for `partnership_or_sponsorship_boundary`. Network membership, broad children's-hospital mission text, generic donation-network language, fundraising events, corporate partner campaigns, generic "support local hospitals" copy, and repeated profile modules do not satisfy this requirement unless the relevant facet disclosure is specifically attributed to the submitted organization or project and adds facet-specific information beyond the shared source-family template.
